<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 6 日，星期日 06:21:03 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Record Amounts of Money Sent Back Home End Up Aiding Autocratic Regimes]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>向发展中国家的汇款达到创纪录的 6,470 亿美元，帮助了穷人，但帮助从尼加拉瓜到塔吉克斯坦的强人继续掌权<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826142/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="非洲移民最近乘坐木船从地中海驶向欧洲。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>非洲移民最近乘坐木船从地中海驶向欧洲。琼·马特乌·帕拉/美联社<span>琼·马特乌·帕拉/美联社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093527"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001093527"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ryan-dube" itemprop="url" rel="author">瑞安·杜贝</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 5 日晚上 11:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/record-amounts-of-money-sent-back-home-end-upaiding-autocratic-regimes-5bd9cdd9"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>秘鲁利马—— <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-worlds-biggest-economies-cautiously-open-their-doors-to-more-foreign-workers-664c3549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界各地的移民</a>人数比以往任何时候都多，数百万人寄回创纪录数额的现金，为乌干达的小企业提供资金，并养活从厄瓜多尔到尼泊尔的家庭。</p><p>但汇款也为脆弱国家和独裁政权提供了关键支持，这些国家和独裁政权依靠公民在海外赚到的钱来维持经济运转。</p><p>据华盛顿的美洲对话政策小组称，在委内瑞拉，三分之一的家庭依赖超过 730 万逃离<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bidens-new-border-rules-dont-deter-desperate-venezuelans-9a3c022b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">该国经济崩溃的</a>移民汇回的钱。经济学家表示，在许多前苏联官员统治的中亚，移民汇出的资金如此之多，以至于这些资金足以弥补本国的贸易赤字。在尼加拉瓜，汇款对丹尼尔·奥尔特加总统政权的税收收入至关重要，以至于一些经济学家表示，减少资金流动将成为一种政治抵抗。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830339?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “如果没有汇款，国民经济就会崩溃，”流亡的尼加拉瓜经济学家恩里克·萨恩斯说。 “从宏观经济角度来看，奥尔特加将陷入大麻烦。”</p><p>不断增长的资金流动给寻求对独裁领导人施加经济压力的改革者带来了挑战。但限制汇款会伤害留在家乡并依赖汇款的弱势移民家庭。</p><p> “汇款是我们能处理的最困难的问题之一，”华盛顿战略与国际研究中心的政治学家瑞安·伯格说。 “没有人真正想触及这个问题，因为从政策角度来看，当我们都知道人们正在受苦时，谁会试图干预汇款，以此向独裁政权施压。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826103?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名抗议者在 2020 年尼泊尔加德满都的反政府示威活动中受伤。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Skanda Gautam/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>根据世界银行的数据，自 2010 年以来，流入发展中国家的汇款几乎翻了一番，去年达到创纪录的 6470 亿美元，超过了这些国家的外国直接投资和国际发展援助。</p><p>尼泊尔是一个年轻而脆弱的民主国家，汇款占国内生产总值的近四分之一，移民工人的流入有助于抑制人们对政府处理流行病和最近经济衰退的愤怒，吉万·巴尼亚(Jeevan Baniya)说。位于加德满都的巴哈社会科学研究所的移民问题专家。</p><p> “如果没有汇款流入，我们可能会经历某种社会或政治动荡，”巴尼亚说。 “汇款最终会加强现有的权力结构。”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>您是否向居住在其他国家/地区的家人或朋友汇款？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>在埃及，移民汇出的资金提供的收入是政府从国有苏伊士运河获得的收入的三倍，而向墨西哥的汇款超过了国际旅游业和石油出口产生的美元。</p><p> “汇款已成为发展中国家的金融生命线，”世界银行经济学家兼汇款专家迪利普·拉塔(Dilip Ratha)表示。</p><p>自Covid-19大流行以来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/immigrants-share-of-the-u-s-labor-force-grows-to-a-new-high-67805c45?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，美国和欧洲移民</a>激增，刺激了每年数百万笔资金转移，每笔资金往往每次只有几百美元。移民正在抵达劳动力短缺的富裕国家，使他们能够找到薪水更高的工作并寄更多的钱回家。</p><p>一些经济学家表示，如果汇款数额太大，可能会损害长期发展并造成治理问题。</p><p>杜克大学经济学家康奈尔·富伦坎普表示，一旦汇款占一个国家国内生产总值的 5% 至 10% 以上，就会开始出现问题。他说，这笔钱可能会降低那些接受资金的人的工作积极性。他们还可以抑制对政府解决首先导致移民的国内问题的要求。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826044?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">去年，斯里兰卡汇款下降引发了一场经济危机，抗议者冲进总理办公室要求他辞职。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Rafiq Maqbool/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="857" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826050?width=1260&amp;height=857" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">美国对古巴加强经济制裁导致汇款减少，导致 2021 年该岛发生骚乱。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：拉蒙·埃斯皮诺萨/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>为国际货币基金组织撰写有关汇款的研究报告的富伦坎普表示：“如果你收到汇款，你就不太关心自己后院到底发生了什么，因为你总是可以向海外亲戚寻求更多的汇款。” 。 “政客们都很清楚。”</p><p>世界上一些最依赖汇款的国家都受到独裁政权的统治，那里的人们几乎没有经济机会——除了离开。</p><p>总部位于菲律宾的亚洲开发银行经济学家罗曼·莫吉列夫斯基表示：“这些国家的货币比原本更坚挺，而且通胀也比原本要低。”</p><p>根据世界银行的数据，在中亚国家塔吉克斯坦，来自主要在俄罗斯工作的移民的资金占该国国内生产总值的近一半。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826377?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>那里的汇款帮助了独裁总统埃莫马利·拉赫蒙</p>据研究该国的学者称，他将继续保持对权力长达三十年的掌控。居住在内布拉斯加州的塔吉克斯坦政治学家纳夫鲁兹·内克巴赫特肖夫 (Navruz Nekbakhtshoev) 表示，这些汇款可以为国内家庭提供食物，从而平息人们的不满和对官员的要求。年轻人为现金流提供资金的大量外流也导致那些可能挑战政治现状的人被赶走。<p></p><p> “这有助于稳定政权，”他说。 “只要人民有这条退路，专制政权基本上就能继续掌权。”</p><p>经济学家表示，由于乌克兰战争和西方制裁， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russias-economy-is-starting-to-come-undone-431a2878?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯经济陷入困境</a>，移民的就业机会可能会减少，从而影响汇款。</p><p>欧亚集团该地区问题专家扎卡里·维特林表示，这促使塔吉克斯坦和其他中亚国家政府试图通过促进移民前往土耳其和英国等其他地方的途径来<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-ukraine-kazakhstan-central-asia-11658439761?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">减少对俄罗斯的依赖</a>。</p><p>在脆弱的民主国家，汇款大幅下降可能会引发动乱。在斯里兰卡，来自海外侨民的收入超过了茶叶出口收入，2020 年至 2022 年，汇款减少了近一半。这导致了<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sri-lanka-economy-to-contract-by-more-than-6-in-2022-central-bank-governor-says-11657978849?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">国际收支危机</a>，耗尽了该国的外汇储备，并使其陷入困境。无法支付进口或偿还外债。在大规模骚乱中， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sri-lankas-president-misses-resignation-deadline-after-fleeing-country-11657792519?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">总统去年逃离该国</a>。</p><p>在其他地方，由于统治者压制异议，汇款减少可能会迫使更多人离开。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-826072?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一位顾客最近在委内瑞拉加拉加斯用美元购买食品，汇款帮助那里的人们度过了经济衰退。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：GABY ORAA/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>古巴在 20 世纪 90 年代其恩主苏联解体并导致经济急剧萎缩后，首次允许汇款。历史学家说，这个西半球唯一的共产主义国家意识到，允许一些人离开可以成为硬通货的重要来源。</p><p>纽约巴鲁克学院教授、有关古巴的书籍作者特德·亨肯表示：“从某种程度上来说，汇款可以为这个不起作用的系统注入润滑脂。” “仅就国内生产总值而言，迈阿密或马德里的古巴人对古巴政府来说可能更有价值。”</p><p>然后，从 2019 年到 2021 年，由于疫情和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/trump-administration-tightens-sanctions-against-cuba-venezuela-1541110328?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国更严厉的制裁</a>（部分目的是阻止古巴军方从汇款中获利），古巴的汇款下降了 70% 以上。时任国务卿迈克·蓬佩奥 (Mike Pompeo) 在 2020 年表示，古巴军方正在从古巴裔美国人寄回给家人的“善意、慷慨的资金”中抽取一部分。</p><p>随着古巴旅游业也枯竭，人们走上街头， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cuba-cracks-down-on-protests-amid-worst-economic-crisis-in-decades-11626108212?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">要求结束自 1959 年以来掌权的政权</a>。</p><p>总部位于迈阿密、追踪古巴经济的公司哈瓦那咨询集团总裁埃米利奥·莫拉莱斯表示，如今，汇款仍远低于大流行前的水平， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/cuban-migrants-head-to-the-u-s-in-large-numbers-11661353200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国的古巴移民家庭</a>越来越多地为亲属离开古巴提供资金。</p><p> “局势如此混乱，人们宁愿投资让家人离开古巴，”他说。</p><p>宾夕法尼亚大学委内瑞拉经济学家安吉尔·阿尔瓦拉多表示，委内瑞拉经济在过去十年中<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/paradise-lost-venezuelas-path-from-riches-to-ruin-11549570900?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">萎缩了 75%</a> ，对于在尼古拉斯·马杜罗总统的独裁和破产政府统治下留在该国的人们来说，汇款至关重要。 。</p><p> “你可以问，‘委内瑞拉的人们如何不死于饥饿？’”阿尔瓦拉多说。 “答案是他们至少有一个孩子住在国外，正在寄钱购买食物和药品。”</p><p>在尼加拉瓜，奥尔特加总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/nicaraguas-political-crisis-descends-into-dark-days-1528235963?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">暴力镇压抗议活动</a>后，2018 年至 2022 年的汇款额增加了一倍多。美洲对话的尼加拉瓜经济学家曼努埃尔·奥罗斯科表示，今年，它们预计将占该国 GDP 的 33% 左右，是拉丁美洲比例最高的国家之一。</p><p> 45 岁的尼加拉瓜人玛尔塔·奥尔特加 (Marta Ortega) 在哥斯达黎加的家里找到了做饭的工作，她说她从未想过自己的调动可以支持她反对的政权。她只是想帮助她的母亲。</p><p> “这并不很多，”奥尔特加说。 “但这确实很重要。”</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —乌干达坎帕拉的 Nicholas Bariyo、圣保罗的 Samantha Pearson 和<em>哥伦比亚波哥大</em>的 Jenny Carolina González 对本文做出了贡献。</p><p>写信给 Ryan Dubé： <a href="mailto:ryan.dube@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ryan.dube@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 03:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/record-amounts-of-money-sent-back-home-end-upaiding-autocratic-regimes-5bd9cdd9</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/record-amounts-of-money-sent-back-home-end-upaiding-autocratic-regimes-5bd9cdd9<author><![CDATA[Ryan Dubé]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>中小型企业</category><category>经济表现/指标</category><category>经济增长/衰退</category><category>贸易/外部支付</category><category>资本流动/无形贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>股票市场</category><category>商品/金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>IWE过滤器</category><category>日常市场/财经新闻</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>小的</category><category>中型企业</category><category>经济表现</category><category>指标</category><category>经济增长</category><category>经济衰退</category><category>贸易</category><category>外部支付</category><category>资本流动</category><category>无形贸易</category><category>经济新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>人类迁徙</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>股票市场</category><category>商品</category><category>金融市场新闻</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>c&amp;e 排除过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>伊威过滤器</category><category>常规市场</category><category>财经新闻</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The West Sanctioned Russia’s Billionaires. Now They Are Fighting Back.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>俄罗斯商界精英受到制裁向普京施压，但乌克兰战争仍在继续<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001110241"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="593" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829735?width=860&amp;height=593" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">弗拉基米尔·普京总统呼吁商界精英回到俄罗斯。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：亚历山大·卡扎科夫/克里姆林宫/Shutterstock </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001110241"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/max-colchester" itemprop="url" rel="author">马克斯·科尔切斯特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 5 日晚上 11:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-sanctioned-russias-billionaires-now-they-are-fighting-back-836ee65"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>伦敦——一年多前，西方推出了新的外交政策武器，向克里姆林宫施压，要求其停止乌克兰战争：它对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-oligarchs-sanctions-what-to-know-11646264511?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">一百多名俄罗斯知名商人</a>及其家人实施了制裁，希望他们能够敦促俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">弗拉基米尔·普京(Vladimir Putin)</a>给予支持。加强他的扩张主义计划。</p><p>到目前为止，该策略尚未奏效。战争仍在肆虐，很少<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-oligarch-and-putin-critic-renounces-citizenship-over-ukraine-war-11667326936?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">有俄罗斯亿万富翁</a>公开谴责普京或出售其俄罗斯资产。与此同时，少数财力雄厚的寡头正在反击，加大了在英国和欧盟法院的法律挑战力度<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/sanctioned-russian-oligarch-explores-ways-to-ease-the-pain-of-restrictions-11661436206?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，试图取消包括旅行禁令和资产冻结在内的限制</a>。</p><p>这些法律斗争将考验俄罗斯商人是否可以利用西方对法治的执着来破坏其自身的外交政策目标。它还将揭露他们对制裁的主要批评；许多目标对普京没有影响力，制裁非但没有对俄罗斯总统施加压力，反而可能将心怀不满的西方化寡头重新推向他的怀抱。</p><p>认证反洗钱专家协会的制裁专家乔治·沃洛辛 (George Voloshin) 表示：“我们以前从未见过这么多拥有如此广泛国际影响力的亿万富翁同时受到如此大规模的制裁。”该协会分享打击洗钱的最佳实践。洗钱。鉴于这些寡头大多数并不属于普京的核心圈子，“制裁对他们及其家人来说是痛苦的，但从政策的角度来看，它们并不是真正有效。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829721?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">罗曼·阿布拉莫维奇的律师辩称，西方制裁使他无法在促进乌克兰战争和平方面发挥作用。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Ozan Kose/法新社/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>西方政府官员表示，大规模制裁应被视为对俄罗斯更广泛镇压的一部分，其中包括禁止向该国出口主要产品，旨在削弱其经济，但这些举措的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-attacked-russias-economy-the-result-is-another-stalemate-99ec913b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">效果也有限</a>。他们还认为，当克里姆林宫的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/story/russias-oligarchs-lifestyles-of-the-rich-and-sanctioned-3a54627b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">庇护让他们变得富有</a>时，他们不应该被允许继续他们的正常生活，而克里姆林宫却继续进行非法入侵。</p><p>美国财政部外国资产控制办公室前主任、该律师事务所合伙人约翰·史密斯表示，其目的是“开始剥夺对普京的支持，因为寡头拥有巨大的政治和经济影响力”。莫里森·福斯特。 “我们还没有达到那个临界点。但这并不意味着我们不会达到那个临界点。”</p><p>法庭文件显示，罗曼·阿布拉莫维奇的律师最近出现在卢森堡法庭，对<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/roman-abramovich-other-sanctioned-russian-oligarchs-fight-back-in-court-11657978210?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">欧盟对其俄罗斯客户的制裁</a>提出上诉，称这一指定阻止了他作为俄罗斯和乌克兰之间和平谈判渠道的“有效干预”。</p><p>这位亿万富翁、英国足球队切尔西足球俱乐部的前老板也提出了其他几位寡头在法庭上提出的论点；仅仅因为他是一名俄罗斯商人，他就受到了不公平的攻击，而且他与普京的关系被夸大了。法院将在未来几个月内做出裁决。</p><p>与此同时，尤金·施维德勒</p>成为第一个在法庭上挑战英国对俄罗斯制裁制度的人。法庭文件显示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-oligarchs-private-jets-find-refuge-in-dubai-but-cant-leave-11649496610?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，阿布拉莫维奇的前商业同事</a>声称，制裁给他的家庭带来了“严重困难”，而且是不成比例的。文件显示，这位拥有英国和美国国籍的亿万富翁还声称从未持有俄罗斯护照，自 2007 年以来就没有见过普京本人。<p></p><p>英国政府在辩护中表示，施维德勒应该继续受到制裁，以便他可以向阿布拉莫维奇施加压力，而阿布拉莫维奇又可以向普京施压。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=499CE186-AAD0-4E16-8761-717D8E355E4C&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fthe-west-sanctioned-russias-billionaires-now-they-are-fighting-back-836ee65&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">俄罗斯入侵乌克兰后，一些与俄罗斯寡头有联系的超级游艇离开了面临制裁的国家的港口。以下是当局和互联网侦探如何使用地图软件、卫星图像和目击者描述来追踪他们。插图：伊芙·哈特利<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>既然他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/roman-abramovich-moved-assets-to-an-island-in-the-english-channel-now-he-faces-a-probe-11653403549?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">无法在西方获得财富</a>，一些受制裁的寡头可能会更加依赖他们在俄罗斯的资产和普京的庇护。许多人被法律禁止前往西方国家。阿布拉莫维奇多年来一直在伦敦开展业务，直到 2018 年英国政府没有续签他的签证，现在他往返于俄罗斯、土耳其和以色列之间。受到美国制裁的安德烈·古里耶夫(Andrei Guryev)将其持有俄罗斯化肥巨头PhosAgro股份的控股公司从瑞士迁至俄罗斯低税区。</p><p>普京呼吁商人返回俄罗斯。</p><p>他在二月份的国情咨文演讲中表示，“拿着帽子到处乱跑，乞讨自己的钱，没有任何意义，最重要的是，它一事无成。” “不要再执着于过去，诉诸法庭至少要拿回一些东西。” <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>近几十年来，制裁已成为西方对付流氓国家的重要工具。它们的成本相对较低，可以避免全面的军事干预，并且可以有针对性地造成最大的痛苦，而附带的经济损失却很小。多年来，伊朗、朝鲜、委内瑞拉和叙利亚政权都成为美国及其盟友的攻击目标。</p><p>对与一国政府有联系的商界精英进行协调一致的制裁是这一工具的最新发展。 2022 年，入侵后不久，欧盟和英国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-approves-new-russia-sanctions-as-divisions-emerge-11647345065?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">修改了自己的制裁规则</a>，以确保它们适用于尽可能多的俄罗斯人。</p><p>迄今为止，制裁的记录好坏参半。分析人士表示，仅靠制裁很少能实现大规模政权更迭或迫使一个国家放弃关键外交政策目标。此外，它们可能会激起受制裁民众的愤怒，因为他们认为某个政权可以重新针对西方。</p><p>然而，制裁可能会实现更有限或不太明显的目标，例如阻止其他可能想要帮助俄罗斯的人。例如，西方官员表示，由于<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">担心遭到报复性制裁</a>，中国基本上没有向俄罗斯提供武器。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="462" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829723?width=700&amp;height=462" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">俄罗斯亿万富翁奥列格·德里帕斯卡成为俄罗斯入侵乌克兰后不久最早批评乌克兰战争的寡头之一。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maxim Shemetov/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>沃洛辛表示，尽管备受瞩目的寡头们在欧洲法庭上抵制制裁，但到目前为止，他们还没有对美国的制裁提出质疑，“原因很简单，他们认为自己不会获胜”。外国资产控制办公室长期以来一直赢得受制裁个人提出的法律挑战。 2021年，俄罗斯工业大亨奥列格·德里帕斯卡<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russian-tycoon-oleg-deripaska-loses-suit-to-lift-u-s-sanctions-11623795556?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">起诉美国财政部</a>，要求推翻其在2014年俄罗斯吞并克里米亚后实施的制裁，但败诉，开创了其他案件的先例。</p><p>一些俄罗斯人成功地辩称，他们卷入这场扫荡是不公平的。欧盟最近取消了对瓦格纳雇佣军领导人叶夫根尼·普里戈任的母亲的制裁，此前欧盟<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-court-strikes-down-sanctions-on-wagner-group-founders-mother-a93f01c6?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">承认错误地表示维奥莱塔·普里戈任仍然控制着与其儿子有关联的公司</a>。尼基塔·马泽平 (Nikita Mazepin) 是一名一级方程式赛车手，其父亲迪姆特里 (Dimtry) 是化肥巨头乌拉尔化学公司 (Uralchem) 的前所有者。尼基塔·马泽平 (Nikita Mazepin) 获得了欧盟制裁的临时救济，理由是这阻止了他追求赛车生涯，而且他在战争中没有发挥任何作用。然而，英国拒绝了类似的上诉。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829724?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">尼基塔·马泽平 (Nikita Mazepin) 获得欧盟制裁的临时救济。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Maksim Konstantinov/Sopa Images/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>对于寡头来说，到目前为止，他们还没有动力公开批评俄罗斯政府或战争，以期获得他们的资产。德里帕斯卡在入侵后不久成为第一批批评战争的寡头之一。去年12月，俄罗斯法院下令没收他在索契拥有的一家豪华酒店大楼。他仍然受到美国、英国和欧洲的制裁。</p><p>然而，有变化的迹象。亿万富翁奥列格·廷科夫（Oleg Tinkov）在战争开始后放弃了俄罗斯公民身份，并多次批评普京在乌克兰的行为，但无论如何都受到了英国政府的制裁。但今年夏天，英国将他从名单上除名。英国外交部在一份声明中表示，“考虑了此案的所有因素，包括廷科夫先生在被指定制裁后采取的行动”，已将他免职。</p><p>英国还将列夫·卡西斯 (Lev Khasis) 除名，他辞去了俄罗斯联邦储蓄银行 (Sberbank) 的高级职务，并在战前逃离了俄罗斯。他拒绝发表评论。</p><p>写信给马克斯·科尔切斯特<a href="mailto:Max.Colchester@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Max.Colchester@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 03:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-sanctioned- Russias-billionaires-now-they-are-fighting-back-836ee65</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-west-sanctioned- Russias-billionaires-now-they-are-fighting-back-836ee65<author><![CDATA[Max Colchester]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>法规/政府政策</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>弗拉基米尔普京</category><category>规定</category><category>政府政策</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国际制裁</category><category>高净值个人</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Russia and China Sent Large Naval Patrol Near Alaska]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>美国派出四艘驱逐舰监视俄罗斯和中国船只<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113918"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830486?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">据美国官员称，俄罗斯和中国船只驶近阿拉斯加，但从未进入美国领海。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：乔恩·纳斯卡/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113918"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/michael-r-gordon" itemprop="url" rel="author">迈克尔·R·戈登</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/nancy-a-youssef" itemprop="url" rel="author">南希·A·优素福</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 5 日晚上 8:55 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-and-china-sent-large-naval-patrol-near-alaska-127de28b"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>本周早些时候，俄罗斯和中国的联合海军部队在阿拉斯加海岸附近巡逻，美国专家表示，这似乎是接近美国海岸的最大此类舰队。</p><p>据美国官员称，11 艘俄罗斯和中国船只驶近阿留申群岛。这些船只从未进入美国领海并已离开，并受到四艘美国驱逐舰和 P-8 海神飞机的跟踪。</p><p> “这是历史性的第一次，”传统基金会高级研究员、退役海军上尉布伦特·萨德勒说。 “考虑到<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">乌克兰战争</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/taiwan-unveils-dates-for-u-s-stops-by-vice-president-despite-chinas-protests-17106008?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">台湾周边紧张局势</a>的背景，此举极具挑衅性。”</p><p>美国北方司令部发言人证实，俄罗斯和中国在阿拉斯加附近进行了联合海军巡逻，但没有具体说明船只数量或具体位置。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “我们指挥下的空中和海上资产开展了行动，以确保美国和加拿大的防御。巡逻队仍在国际水域，不被视为威胁，”该司令部在一份声明中表示。</p><p>参议院军事委员会共和党成员、阿拉斯加州参议员丹·沙利文表示，这次巡逻提醒人们，美国已经进入“独裁侵略的新时代”，并对美国强有力的反应表示赞赏。</p><p>俄罗斯和中国驻华盛顿大使馆没有立即回应置评请求。</p><p><em>随着新闻的发展而更新。</em></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sun, 06 Aug 2023 00:55:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-and-china-sent-large-naval-patrol-near-alaska-127de28b</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ Russia-and-china-sent-large-naval-patrol-near-alaska-127de28b<author><![CDATA[Michael R. GordonNancy A. Youssef]]></author><category>专有的</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>武装部队</category><category>海军</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[With China Attending, Ukraine Peace Discussions Inch Forward]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>沙特主办的会谈排除了俄罗斯，缩小了乌克兰与主要发展中国家在结束战争的公平条件方面的分歧<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113797"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830480?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰总统泽伦斯基敦促其大使加紧努力，为基辅的立场赢得全球支持。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：POU/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113797"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/laurence-norman" itemprop="url" rel="author">劳伦斯·诺曼</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/stephen-kalin" itemprop="url" rel="author">斯蒂芬·卡林</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 5 日下午 6:09 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-china-attending-ukraine-peace-discussions-inch-forward-40855818"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>周六，来自美国、中国、印度和乌克兰等 42 个国家的高级官员<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/in-saudi-arabias-ukraine-peace-talks-how-to-measure-success-fedb58ea?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">在沙特阿拉伯进行讨论</a>后，围绕持久、公平和平解决乌克兰战争达成国际共识的努力取得了进展。</p><p>乌克兰及其西方支持者表示，此次会谈是为了争取全球支持，为结束有利于乌克兰的战争创造条件。许多发展中大国在这场冲突上基本上保持中立。</p><p>吉达会谈结束后，外交官们表示，人们普遍认为，尊重乌克兰主权和领土完整等国际法核心原则应成为乌克兰和俄罗斯未来和平谈判的核心。据知情人士透露，双方就战争的全球影响开展更详细的工作达成了一致，包括中国在内的大多数与会国家似乎愿意在未来几周内以目前的形式再次举行会议，俄罗斯除外。闭门会谈。</p><p>吉达会谈是在六月于哥本哈根进行初步讨论后举行的。美国和欧洲官员强调，讨论不是结束冲突的谈判，也不会寻求制定具体的解决方案。</p><p>周六的会议地点具有重要的象征意义，因为乌克兰、美国和欧洲都在努力<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/saudi-arabia-to-host-ukraine-peace-talks-as-part-of-western-effort-to-woo-global-south-244f03f0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">加强南半球对基辅的支持</a>。西方外交官表示，选择沙特作为主办国的部分原因是希望<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-drawn-out-ukraine-war-opens-new-risks-for-china-e5fe8b7c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">说服中国参与</a>，因为利雅得和北京保持着密切关系。</p><p>去年，美国指责沙特阿拉伯与俄罗斯站在一起，维持高油价，从而支撑莫斯科的财政，此后，沙特阿拉伯正试图在乌克兰外交中发挥更大作用。</p><p>一位美国官员表示：“沙特东道主的外交接触功不可没。”</p><p>许多西方国家首都对俄罗斯总统<a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/vladimir-putin">普京</a>今年有兴趣进行和平谈判深表怀疑。俄罗斯没有表现出放弃极端主义要求的迹象，例如承认其吞并乌克兰领土，包括其军队无法控制的乌克兰地区。</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>莫斯科就此次会谈发出了复杂的信号。克里姆林宫表示将密切关注，但俄罗斯外交部发言人称这些讨论是一场骗局。</p><p>乌克兰总统泽伦斯基本周敦促其大使加紧努力，为基辅的立场赢得全球支持。当外交官们在吉达交谈时，俄罗斯对乌克兰发动了新的导弹袭击。</p><p> “俄罗斯本周六向乌克兰发射了另一轮导弹。乌克兰外交部长德米特罗·库莱巴（Dmytro Kuleba）在推特上写道：“俄罗斯不停止就不会停止。” “国际社会必须集中精力实现公正和持久的和平。”</p><p>哥本哈根会议和吉达会议之间最大的区别在于出席人数——参加或拨入周六会谈的国家数量是其两倍多。其中包括欧洲国家、日本、韩国、印度尼西亚、土耳其和南非。</p><p>最重要的是，曾受邀参加哥本哈根会议但没有参加的中国派出了代表团前往吉达。西方外交官表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-and-allies-look-at-potential-china-role-in-ending-ukraine-war-2d6cbb4d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">，北京在会谈中总体上发挥了建设性作用</a>。</p><p>外交官表示，作为俄罗斯最重要的外国盟友，中国被视为对推动会谈至关重要，并可能为讨论莫斯科的一些红线和担忧提供一种途径。沙特阿拉伯最高领导层和乌克兰极力推动北京参加。</p><p>在会谈中， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-urges-cessation-of-hostilities-peace-talks-to-end-ukraine-war-ae45829a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">中国提出了一项停火与和平谈判以结束战争的十二点计划</a>，该计划于二月份首次宣布。欧洲外交官反驳称，无条件停火可能只会造成冲突冻结，并让俄罗斯巩固对乌克兰领土的控制。</p><p> “他们得到了实时反馈，这是一次很好的交流，”一位知情人士表示。</p><p>一名美国高级官员表示，国家安全顾问杰克·沙利文和负责政治事务的副国务卿维多利亚·纽兰在场外会见了中国代表团团长、北京和平特使李辉。</p><p> “有中国人在这里真是太好了，”这位美国官员说。</p><p>外交官们还表示，哥本哈根会议上出现的一些分歧似乎已经缩小。在这些会谈中，乌克兰敦促主要发展中国家接受泽连斯基的和平计划，其核心是要求只有在俄罗斯军队完全撤军后才能开始和平，但一些发展中国家表示不会这样做。</p><p>在吉达，乌克兰和主要发展中国家似乎更渴望寻求共识。一位欧洲高级官员表示，乌克兰没有再次推动其和平计划被接受，其他国家也没有坚持要求基辅放弃该计划。乌克兰要求俄罗斯撤军的要求也没有发生任何交火。两名外交官表示，乌克兰没有强调这一点，也没有受到发展中国家的质疑。</p><p>虽然第三次会议的日期尚未确定，但就双轨进程达成了一致。乌克兰将继续与驻基辅的外国大使讨论和平条件。</p><p>沙特阿拉伯计划针对乌克兰和平计划中提出的具体问题提出一组工作组，其中一些涉及战争的全球影响。这可能包括核安全、环境溢出和粮食安全——最近几天，联合国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/russia-says-it-is-pulling-out-of-ukraine-grain-deal-68190d1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">斡旋的黑海粮食倡议的失败</a>凸显了这一问题。</p><p> “共识是，这不是一场欧洲战争，但对全球粮食、能源和经济稳定产生影响，需要所有人参与才能达成和解的最终结果，”一位来自其中一个国家的外交官表示。非西方国家。</p><p>写信给劳伦斯·诺曼<a href="mailto:laurence.norman@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">（laurence.norman@wsj.com）</a>和史蒂芬·卡林（ <a href="mailto:stephen.kalin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Stephen.kalin@wsj.com）</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 22:09:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-china-attending-ukraine-peace-discussions-inch-forward-40855818</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/with-china-attending-ukraine-peace-discussions-inch-forward-40855818<author><![CDATA[Laurence NormanStephen Kalin]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Pakistan Convicts Opposition Figure, Signals Election Delay]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>经过数段军事统治后，这两项举措危及脆弱的民主<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113250"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830443?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">前总理伊姆兰·汗于今年夏天早些时候离开法庭。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：aamir qureshi/法新社/Getty Images </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113250"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/saeed-shah" itemprop="url" rel="author">赛义德·沙阿</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 5 日下午 2:10（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>巴基斯坦伊斯兰堡——周六，法院判处前总理伊姆兰·汗入狱，并且政府表示<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/bombing-in-pakistan-kills-at-least-40-a86aa839?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">今年的选举</a>将被推迟，巴基斯坦停滞不前的民主进程遭遇挫折。</p><p>巴基斯坦有过四个直接军事统治时期。但自2008年以来，它经历了最长的民主政府时期。</p><p>据政府及其律师称，该国最大反对党领导人汗被伊斯兰堡一家法院判犯有腐败罪，并判处三年监禁。汗在本案以及自去年四月<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supporters-of-pakistans-imran-khan-defy-top-court-block-vote-in-parliament-11649522558?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">被赶下台</a>以来政府针对他提起的数十起其他法律案件中坚称自己无罪。他的政党表示，他面临着一场将他从政坛驱逐出去的运动。如果定罪成立，汗先生将无法参加选举。</p><p>汗先生的一名律师表示，他计划对定罪提出上诉。周六判决后不久，警方在这位政客家中逮捕了他。</p><p>汗先生于 2018 年当选，去年因议会不信任投票而被罢免总理职务。还没有哪位巴基斯坦总理完成了完整的五年任期，每位总理都与该国军方发生过冲突。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830444?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴基斯坦拉合尔，警察在伊姆兰·汗的住所外守卫。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：KM Chaudary/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>另外，谢赫巴兹·谢里夫总理领导的政府周六表示，根据宪法规定原定于 11 月初举行的选举将被推迟。法律部长阿扎姆·纳齐姆·塔拉尔表示，宪法还要求根据最近的人口普查结果举行选举，这意味着需要更多时间准备，将投票时间推至2月左右。巴基斯坦今年早些时候进行了人口普查。他说，独立联邦机构巴基斯坦选举委员会将宣布新的选举日期。</p><p>该部长表示，投票可能会在明年二月或三月举行。但巴基斯坦许多人担心，如果选举不能按宪法规定举行，推迟的时间可能会更长。</p><p> “民主的未来是黯淡的，”巴基斯坦律师协会前副主席、律师阿比德·萨奇说。 “当整个宪法都陷入沉睡时，我认为在不久的将来不会举行选举。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830465?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Former Prime Minister Imran Khan is escorted through Islamabad after his arrest Saturday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: WK Yousafzai/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The case that led to Khan&#39;s conviction relates to a watch given to him by Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman when Khan was prime minister. The watch was later sold by Khan. He denies any wrongdoing over that sale. Other gifts officially presented to Khan when he was prime minister also figured in the case.</p><p> The bespoke diamond-encrusted watch featured a picture on its dial of the Kaaba, a stone building in Mecca, Saudi Arabia, where Muslims go for pilgrimage.</p><p> Prime ministers are allowed under the law to buy such official gifts, for a portion of their value. The government alleged that there were irregularities in the valuation of the watch carried out for Khan to purchase it and in the disclosure of the proceeds from the sale of the gift. The court, in its guilty ruling, said Khan&#39;s “dishonesty has been established beyond doubt.”</p><p> “Politicians get discredited over such trivial matters,” Mohsin Dawar, a lawmaker whose party is a minor part of the current coalition government, said on X, the website formerly known as Twitter. “政客不断地被利用，然后像伊姆兰·汗一样被抛弃。 We keep going round and round in circles.”</p><p> In recent months Pakistan, which is <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pakistan-clinches-3-billion-in-imf-rescue-lending-698e63ce?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">mired in a deep economic crisis</a> , has seen a broad political crackdown on Khan and his Tehreek-e-Insaf party. Thousands of Khan&#39;s supporters were arrested earlier this year after protests at military sites over his arrest in May on corruption charges. The courts freed him days later on bail.</p><p> “I appeal to you to not sit quietly in your homes,” Khan said in a video message that he had earlier recorded in the expectation he would be arrested again. His party shared the video on Saturday after the court announced its verdict. “My struggle is not to gain any personal benefits—I am doing this for the nation, for you, for the future of your children. If you don&#39;t stand up for your rights, you will live like slaves.”</p><p> Khan, a former cricket star, was seen as having the backing of Pakistan&#39;s powerful military in the 2018 election. After he was ousted, he led a fiery protest campaign, blaming the military for conspiring with other political parties to remove him. The military and ruling party deny this, saying he was dismissed through democratic means.</p><p> Fear of jail continues to grip his supporters, with only small numbers coming out to protest the verdict on Saturday. Many were rounded up by police outside Khan&#39;s home. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830466?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Security members stand guard in Islamabad Saturday amid Imran Khan&#39;s conviction.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: WK Yousafzai/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Khan&#39;s legal team says that due process wasn&#39;t followed in the case, including giving them enough time to call all their defense witnesses.</p><p> The government denied that the arrest is related to the coming election and said the law was just taking its course.</p><p> “Imran must answer for the wrongs while in power,” said Marriyum Aurangzeb, the information minister.</p><p> The current parliament is to come to an end on Aug. 12 at the latest, and a caretaker government—which is supposed to be neutral—is required to preside over the election period.</p><p> Now, the caretaker administration will be in office for longer than the 90-day limit stated in the constitution. A caretaker administration is even more vulnerable to pressure from the military than political governments. Pakistan recently beefed up the decision-making powers of a caretaker administration, allowing it to make deals with foreign governments.</p><p> Both the government and military remain nervous about Khan&#39;s support, and some lawmakers and political experts say they believe that lies behind the decision to delay the election.</p><p class="articleTagLine"> —Waqar Gillani contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Saeed Shah at <a href="mailto:saeed.shah@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">saeed.shah@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 18:10:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/former-pakistani-prime-minister-imran-khan-convicted-in-corruption-case-749f405c<author><![CDATA[Saeed Shah]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Elections</category><category> National/Presidential Elections</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>选举</category><category>国家的</category><category>presidential elections </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S. Warns of Trade Fight Over Canada’s Digital Tax]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Canada is moving ahead with the levy even as other countries agree to delay global tech tax accord until 2025 <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107767"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="588" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829205?width=860&amp;height=588" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Canadian Prime Minister Justin Trudeau and Finance Minister Chrystia Freeland, who has said Canada can&#39;t support an extended pause on digital taxes.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: PATRICK DOYLE/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001107767"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/paul-vieira" itemprop="url" rel="author">保罗·维埃拉</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Aug. 5, 2023 11:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-warns-of-trade-fight-over-canadas-digital-tax-plan-751ffa30"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> OTTAWA—Canada plans to impose a digital-services tax at the start of 2024, a move that bucks <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-minimum-tax-deal-advances-with-partial-reprieve-for-u-s-based-companies-11675363954?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a global consensus on restructuring international taxation</a> and has drawn criticism from US officials.</p><p> Senior members of the Biden administration are attempting to persuade Canada to drop its digital tax plan. Leaders in the US and Canadian business communities say Ottawa&#39;s move will harm commerce and throw the future of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/usmca-takes-effect-but-north-american-trade-tensions-remain-11593604807?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the North American trade deal</a> into doubt.</p><p> Canada&#39;s 3% tax on technology companies&#39; revenue from providing digital services to Canadian users or sales of Canadian user data would start Jan. 1, 2024, and would be retroactive to revenue dating to 2022. Canada&#39;s finance minister, Chrystia Freeland, said last month that the tax is important for Canada&#39;s national interest.</p><p> Companies in the information-technology field can currently operate worldwide while concentrating their profits in their home countries or in small, low-tax jurisdictions; they then pay relatively little tax in the nations where many of their users are.</p><p> A global tax accord, agreed to in the fall of 2021, represents changes to how, where and how much <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/negotiators-see-global-deal-on-taxing-big-tech-companies-within-reach-36b47b10?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">multinational companies are taxed around the world</a> , but it has yet to be implemented. The accord aims to reallocate the taxation of some $200 billion in corporate profits across the globe, a move taken to adapt the tax system to new ways of doing business internationally made possible by advances in information technology.</p><p> Canada signed on to the global deal with a caveat: If not implemented by the start of 2024, Canada would impose its own digital-service tax. Canada first came forward with its plan to tax technology companies in the fall of 2020, with the levy meant to apply as of January 2022.</p><p> In Paris last month, 138 countries agreed to a <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-companies-score-partial-reprieve-from-global-minimum-tax-deal-c5c14d87?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">one-year delay in implementation</a> of the tax accord&#39;s first phase, to early 2025. Canada didn&#39;t agree to the delay and said it would move ahead with plans to implement its own digital-services tax. On Friday, Canada issued guidance on how the proposed digital tax would be applied.</p><p> Freeland said Ottawa&#39;s earlier decision to delay its digital tax for two years, even though other European countries kept pre-existing digital taxes in place, “was a significant concession by Canada” and that Canada can&#39;t support an extended pause on digital taxes.</p><p> The measures related to digital taxes are separate from another global deal, also led by the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development, to impose <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/global-tax-mess-awaits-u-s-companies-and-congress-isnt-helping-eec13f2c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a 15% minimum tax</a> on large companies in each country where they operate, although the accords are politically linked.</p><p> US Trade Representative Katherine Tai has urged Ottawa <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-urges-canada-to-abandon-digital-service-tax-11645554146?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to abandon the levy</a> , and the US ambassador to Canada, David Cohen, said in an interview published last month in Canada&#39;s National Post that “if Canada decides to proceed alone, you leave the United States with no choice but to take retaliatory measures in the trade context, potentially in the digital trade context, in order to respond to that.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829210?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> US Trade Representative Katherine Tai has called on Canada to abandon the digital-services tax.</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：布莱尔·盖布尔/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>A spokeswoman for the US Embassy in Ottawa didn&#39;t respond to requests for further comment.</p><p> Freeland said that Canadian officials remain in talks with their Group of Seven counterparts about a compromise whereby Canadian interests “can be protected and recognized.”</p><p> A number of European countries, including France, the UK and Italy, had introduced <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-european-nations-claim-progress-on-path-to-removing-digital-taxes-11634244167?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">digital-services taxes</a> before the OECD-led talks secured a global tax deal. The agreement included a standstill on new digital-services taxes until the agreement came into force. Pre-existing digital taxes, such as those in Europe, are still being applied but would be revoked once the accord entered into force. Canadian officials say it is unfair some European jurisdictions can collect taxes from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Meta Platforms</a> and Google parent</p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="company-name">Alphabe</a> t but Canada can&#39;t.<p></p><p> The US trade representative considers digital-services taxes, like the one proposed in Canada, to be discriminatory and a burden on US commerce because the sector is dominated by US companies. France&#39;s tax prompted the Trump administration in 2020 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-suspends-plan-to-impose-tariffs-on-french-luxury-goods-11610041797?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to prepare 25% tariffs on French luxury goods</a> . The threat was withdrawn following the tentative global tax deal.</p><p> The global tax deal might not ultimately come together. In the US, members of Congress are divided on it, with senior Republicans in the House of Representatives warning the Biden administration that the OECD accord could breach US tax treaties by expanding other countries&#39; taxing authority.</p><p> Michael Plowgian, a senior tax official at the US Treasury, told Congress that administration officials, including Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen,</p> are speaking to their Canadian counterparts “to dissuade them from implementing a discriminatory” digital-services tax.<p></p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How should the US respond if Canada implements the digital-services tax?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> “Canada was isolated on this issue” during recent OECD tax negotiations in Paris, Plowgian said in testimony last month before the House Ways and Means Committee. “With respect to Canada, we are exploring all options and we would like to work with Congress to address that issue.”</p><p> Representatives for Google and Meta referred to previous remarks by their respective executives, in which they expressed support for a multilateral agreement on tax treatment for technology companies. Canada and the two technology companies are currently in a dispute over Ottawa&#39;s plan to compel them <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/canada-passes-law-forcing-facebook-google-to-pay-media-for-links-f3e13300?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to compensate news organizations</a> for carrying their links on their platforms. Meta this week said it has begun <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/meta-platforms-to-begin-blocking-news-for-canadian-users-35d35b2b?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">to block access to news links</a> for Canadian users on Facebook and Instagram in response to the Canadian measures.</p><p> Among those pushing Washington to exert economic pressure on Canada is the US Chamber of Commerce, the country&#39;s largest business lobby group.</p><p> “Canada has said that it wants to uphold the OECD process, but its recent actions have kind of belied that,” said Neil Herrington, the chamber&#39;s senior vice president for the Americas. Herrington added a Canadian digital tax threatens to undermine OECD talks by prompting other countries to impose similar levies ahead of a global deal.</p><p> Goldy Hyder, president of the Business Council of Canada, said Freeland needs to reconsider, warning a digital-services levy could complicate efforts to persuade Congress to renew the US-Mexico-Canada trade treaty when it comes up for legislative review in 2026.</p><p> “This is not about taxes, it&#39;s about trade,” said Hyder, whose group represents chief executives at the biggest Canadian companies.</p><p> Write to Paul Vieira at <a href="mailto:paul.vieira@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">paul.vieira@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 15:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-warns-of-trade-fight-over-canadas-digital-tax-plan-751ffa30</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-warns-of-trade-fight-over-canadas-digital-tax-plan-751ffa30<author><![CDATA[Paul Vieira]]></author><category> Trade/External Payments</category><category> Physical Trade</category><category> Economic News</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> Alphabet Cl A</category><category>谷歌</category><category>贸易</category><category>external payments</category><category> physical trade</category><category> economic news </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Police Pursuit of U.S.-Based Activist Embroils Family in Hong Kong]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Elmer Yuen&#39;s relatives, including a pro-Beijing lawmaker, were held and questioned in Chinese city as authorities step up pressure on exiled dissidents <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113271"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="574" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827461?width=860&amp;height=574" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hong Kong legislator Eunice Yung, daughter-in-law of US-based activist Elmer Yuen.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TYRONE SIU/REUTERS </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001113271"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/elaine-yu" itemprop="url" rel="author">Elaine Yu</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 5, 2023 6:50 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-pursuit-of-u-s-based-activist-embroils-family-in-hong-kong-31ae1248"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> HONG KONG—At dawn, officers from Hong Kong&#39;s national-security police burst into the apartment of Derek Yuen and Eunice Yung, the son and daughter-in-law of a high-profile pro-democracy campaigner who criticizes China&#39;s Communist Party from perches abroad.</p><p> The police seized a laptop and mobile phone in the raid last Monday and took Yuen and Yung, who is a pro-Beijing politician in the city&#39;s legislature, to a police station for hours of questioning about the activities of their dissident relative before releasing them without charges, according to Yung.</p><p> Elmer Yuen, the 74-year-old US-based activist who is the focus of the authorities&#39; ire, is one of eight overseas critics of China who are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-takes-its-crackdown-abroad-e626bb6c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">facing arrest warrants in Hong Kong</a> after being accused of national-security crimes. He appeared at a news briefing in Washington last month and another in London on Tuesday, discussing his plans to form an unofficial government in exile.</p><p> Elmer Yuen, who shares his political commentary in lengthy videos posted online, said the authorities&#39; actions against his family members were intended to pressure him to speak out less and to halt his political efforts. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827463?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Pro-democracy activist Elmer Yuen during a protest outside the Chinese consulate in San Francisco.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Michael Ho Wai Lee/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “Of course I worry about my safety and that of my family, but our work has a goal, and a price must be paid,” he told The Wall Street Journal. He said he wouldn&#39;t be deterred “even if they arrest my entire family.”</p><p> The family and the widely diverging politics of its members have been the subject of public discussion in Hong Kong in recent years. They appeared in a 2020 documentary aired by the city&#39;s public broadcaster RTHK, and their story has resonated with many <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/mom-says-come-home-hong-kong-protests-divide-families-11567458226?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Hong Kongers in politically divided homes</a> .</p><p> Yung is the vice chair of a major pro-Beijing political party. Her husband once joked that their daughters&#39; crayons at home were missing a yellow one—the color of the city&#39;s pro-democracy movement—because his wife had removed it.</p><p> After Yung was questioned, she said she was cooperating fully with investigators and hoped her father-in-law and the other dissidents would be arrested soon. “If I know about his whereabouts, I will without a doubt disclose it,” she said.</p><p> Yung and her husband didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Hong Kong&#39;s chief executive, John Lee, has encouraged <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-arrests-four-accused-of-aiding-overseas-activists-6636c125?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">friends and relatives of the wanted dissidents</a> to share tips and said they were eligible, along with other members of the public, for a reward of about $128,000 for capture of each activist.</p><p> Authorities would “go to the ends of the earth” to hunt them down, he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827471?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Hong Kong Chief Executive John Lee has encouraged relatives of dissidents to share information about them.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: isaac lawrence/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Many overseas dissidents, often based in countries that have suspended their extradition agreements with Hong Kong over political concerns in recent years, have publicly distanced themselves from their families in the Chinese city.</p><p> When asked about Yuen&#39;s family, police said they took away a man and two women last Monday, and another three people on Thursday, without naming them. All necessary measures would be taken to arrest those accused of endangering national security and cut off their financial support, police said.</p><p> Steve Li, a senior national-security police official, said the arrest warrants and the bounties are aimed at helping police prepare and gather evidence to prosecute dissidents if they return to Hong Kong.</p><p> The national-security law, imposed by Beijing in 2020, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kong-police-arrest-six-for-sedition-in-fresh-crackdown-11674046056?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been used to suppress dissent</a> , with scores of opponents of Communist Party rule locked up, pro-democracy media outlets and groups forced to shut down and public protests effectively banned.</p><p> More than 100,000 people have left the city to move to the UK and dozens of activists and politicians have fled there and to other safe havens.</p><p> The US and UK governments have criticized Hong Kong authorities for using the security law to pursue dissidents overseas. Beijing accused foreign countries of “harboring criminals.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827475?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Derek Yuen, son of Elmer Yuen, considers himself to be on neither side of the political divide.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TYRONE SIU/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Years of political unrest have caused friction in many Hong Kong households. The divide in the Yuen family, a microcosm of Hong Kong&#39;s political spectrum and one featured in the RTHK program, has become a chasm in the wake of the national-security law.</p><p> As views for or against <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/hong-kongs-crackdown-on-dissent-hits-facebook-pages-11660645491?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Beijing&#39;s tightening control</a> over Hong Kong hardened in the years running up to massive 2019 pro-democracy protests and a subsequent crackdown, the family would meet up for special occasions.</p><p> After Yung&#39;s 2018 marriage to Derek, Yung said she largely avoided discussing politics. “I&#39;d sit aside, take care of the kids, bring out some tea,” she said in the documentary. “There&#39;s a tacit understanding that if you don&#39;t talk about it, I won&#39;t, but if someone does, I&#39;d no doubt speak up.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Does your family history include times when people were targeted for speaking out?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> The episode ran a few months after the security law took effect, and after Elmer Yuen had left the city <strong>.</strong></p><p> Derek Yuen, a scholar and newspaper columnist who considers himself on neither side of the political divide, said at the time it was a tragedy that his father, who didn&#39;t get to spend much time with his grandchildren to begin with, may never return to Hong Kong.</p><p> The elder Yuen has doubled down on his activism abroad, lobbying politicians in Washington. Last year, he and other activists called for a sort of parliament-in-exile for Hong Kong, drawing condemnation from the city&#39;s government. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-827480?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Police outside the High Court in Hong Kong.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Louise Delmotte/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Soon after that, his daughter-in-law Yung cut ties with him, taking out an ad in a newspaper to say she was “a Chinese person with the blood of the great motherland flowing through me.”</p><p> Three years since the documentary aired, the stakes are even higher. Anyone charged and found guilty of assisting the wanted activists faces lengthy jail terms.</p><p> Yung told a popular local radio program in early July that she had warned her husband about links to his father: “You need to be careful, with things like seeing him and money matters,” she said she told him.</p><p> Write to Elaine Yu at <a href="mailto:elaine.yu@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">elaine.yu@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 10:50:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-pursuit-of-us-based-activist-embroils-family-in-hong-kong-31ae1248</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-pursuit-of-us-based-activist-embroils-family-in-hong-kong-31ae1248<author><![CDATA[Elaine Yu]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Civil Unrest</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>Social Issues</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>civil unrest</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>社会问题</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The ‘Unicorn Exercise’ Everyone Wants to Do Now]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> As women embrace strength training, executing a pull-up has become a way for many to show just how strong they are <figure><img src="https://m.wsj.net/video-atmo/20230803/f48278a6-9180-432c-bd18-04bae3ba09ac/4/workout0805pullup1c_1000x562.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Rachel Harrison,47, owns a luxury hospitality firm in New York and achieved her first pull up last month after a bit over one year of training. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108760"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001108760"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/jen-murphy" itemprop="url" rel="author">Jen Murphy</a></span> | Video and <span class="author" itemprop="name">photographs by Adrienne Grunwald for The Wall Street Journal</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 5, 2023 6:00 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/pull-ups-women-strength-aging-b3187fc5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web
          bigtophero
"></div><p> The pull-up has become the ultimate fitness flex for women in midlife.</p><p> This winter, London-based consultant Claire Warner embarked on a pull-up quest, hiring a trainer with the goal of being able to do one unassisted pull-up by summer.</p><p> Pull-ups, says Warner, 45 years old, are “the unicorn exercise,” adding: “Everyone wants to be able to do one.” She can now do three and has set her sights on five.</p><p> As women embrace strength training, executing a pull-up has become a way for many to show just how strong they are. Social-media mentions of<a href="https://www.tiktok.com/discover/female-pull-ups?lang=en" target="_blank" class="icon none">“female pull-ups”</a> have amassed millions of views; stars like comedian Chelsea Handler share <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gFHDuI3oY0g" target="_blank" class="icon none">videos</a> of upper-body gym feats, and executives like Meta&#39;s head of product, Naomi Gleit, <a href="https://www.instagram.com/p/Csemk5ZPXcl/?img_index=2" target="_blank" class="icon none">post</a> about their push-up and pull-up feats. (Her boss, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/mark-zuckerberg">Mark Zuckerberg</a> , <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-mark-zuckerberg-cage-fight-b71fa4ff?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">posts fitness photos, too</a> .) </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/atmospheric/amp.html?guid=E748D7B1-08C8-4476-8002-F57C0E3ABC62" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> London consultant Claire Warner, 45, began her pull-up journey this winter. Video: Claire Warner<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>This body-weight exercise, which taps the back and shoulder muscles, is challenging for anyone, but can be particularly daunting for women, who anatomically tend to have more lower-body strength.</p><p> Kirsten Joyce gave her fitness instructor the stink eye when a pull-up was thrown into her group strength class at Life Time gym. She hopped up to the bar, kicked and squirmed, then dropped down, joking to her instructor: “If I can just do one pull-up in my life, then I&#39;ve made it.”</p><p> Joyce, 33, decided to use the pull-up as her benchmark for overall fitness. She started incorporating exercises that work pull-up muscles, like single arm lat pull downs and pull-up shrugs, into her routine.</p><p> Her motivation? Mothering three children under age 5. “I wanted to be able to keep up with them but also set an example,” says the part-time nurse in Eden Prairie, Minn.</p><p> In July, after five months of training, she got her chin above the pull-up bar and can now do three with good form.</p><h3> The Pull-Up Journey</h3><p> Compared with weighted exercises like back squats or dead lifts, pull-ups can be intimidating, says Lex Dreiss, a trainer at Absolute Power Fitness in Brooklyn, NY</p><p> “As a girl, you&#39;re told that you have a weak upper body compared with boys,” she says. “But that doesn&#39;t mean women can&#39;t do pull-ups.”</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> Many people assume the move is all arm strength, but it&#39;s actually a back-dominant exercise, says Dreiss.</p><p> Traditional pull-ups are performed with an overhand grip, shoulder-width or wider, and engage the upper back muscles, including the latissimus dorsi and rhomboids, the deltoid muscles in the shoulders, and the biceps. The movement also works the core and grip strength.</p><p> Some people try first to do a chin-up, which is slightly easier because it uses an underhand grip versus the pull-up&#39;s overhand grip.</p><p> Getting to a pull-up can take about 12 weeks for someone at a healthy weight and baseline fitness level, says Andrew Jagim, director of sports-medicine research at Mayo Clinic Health System in La Crosse, Wis. For someone new to strength training, 16 weeks is more typical.</p><p> Both pull-ups and chin-ups are body-weight exercises, so someone who is overweight might need more time to develop strength before doing a pull-up, he says.</p><p> Chelsey Wilkins,</p> a trainer at SoHo Strength Lab in New York, recommends clients focus on learning to lower their body weight before they try to pull it up. She prescribes exercises that work grip strength and eccentric strength—where the lowering phase of a movement is slowed down—like carefully lowering your chin down from a pull-up bar. <p></p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          edgetoedge
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/b5150491-4224-463b-9ecb-6907a6a50138.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p> Dreiss has her clients practice hollow body holds, where you lie on the ground, then lift your arms, legs and head up off the ground until your body looks kind of like a banana. “If you&#39;re doing a pull-up properly your body is vertical in this position,” she says.</p><p> With these key muscles strengthened, trainers then focus on technique, using assisted weight pull-up machines or looping a resistance band around the bar and beneath the client&#39;s feet to lighten the load of the pull movement.</p><p> One of Dreiss&#39;s clients, Rachel Harrison, could effortlessly pump out dozens of pull-ups during her time as a young gymnast. When her boyfriend left her for a personal trainer, she set herself a goal of doing an unassisted pull-up before she turns 48 this month, and 10 by October.</p><p> She&#39;s shared her progress on <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/META" class="company-name">Facebook</a> and Instagram, with videos showing her performing aided pull-ups with resistance bands looped around the bottom of her feet, and doing two unassisted chin ups. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829278?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Harrison lowers herself as slowly as possible from the pull-up bar to build strength.</p></figcaption></figure></div><h3> The Rewards</h3><p> As a child, Taylor Trabulus, a New York gallerist, disliked being made to do gym-class pull-ups so much that she got a doctor&#39;s note excusing her from PE As an adult, she assumed she couldn&#39;t pull her body weight up, but within six weeks of working with a trainer in 2020, she was able to do a chin-up.</p><p> “I felt like the biggest badass,” says Trabulus, 35. She can now do five chin-ups and is working on her overhand grip for a pull-up.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>How many pull-ups can you do?加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Warner, the London consultant, says her pull-up aspirations were sparked by a desire to gain muscle mass and remain independent as she aged. Muscle mass decreases approximately 3% to 8% per decade after the age of 30. The rate of decline is even greater after the age of 60.</p><p> Dreiss believes many women shy away from upper-body strength training, particularly pull-ups, because they fear they&#39;ll get bulky muscles. But some relish the view.</p><p> Warner, who used to be self-conscious about her arms and would only wear long sleeves, now proudly goes sleeve-free.</p><p> “I am so in love with my <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/natalie-portman-arms-thor-11657118628?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">muscly arms</a> ,” she says. “People compliment them all the time.”</p><p> Harrison, who owns a luxury hospitality firm in New York, has received dozens of supportive messages since she began posting about pull-ups in May 2022 and has lost around 35 pounds. With stronger muscles around her spine, her back no longer goes out and she can see the striations of muscles in her shoulders when she wears a backless dress.</p><p> “I&#39;m healthier now than I was in my 20s or 30s,” she says.</p><p> Last week she finally nabbed her first unassisted pull-up. “Working out is like life,” she says. “There are times you feel like you&#39;ll never succeed but you need to be mentally strong and keep trying.”</p><p> Write to Jen Murphy at <a href="mailto:workout@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">workout@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 10:00:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pull-ups-women-strength-aging-b3187fc5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/pull-ups-women-strength-aging-b3187fc5<author><![CDATA[Jen Murphy]]></author><category> photo-commission</category><category> WSJ生活工作</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Physical/Mental Fitness</category><category>健康</category><category>生活/生活方式</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>身体的</category><category>mental fitness</category><category>健康</category><category>活的</category><category>生活方式</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Ukraine Struggles to Retake Bakhmut From Dogged Russian Fighters]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Kyiv&#39;s front-line soldiers describe a stalling counteroffensive against forces determined to hold pivotal city <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830017/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="顿涅茨克地区的乌克兰军队一直在努力夺回重要领土。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Ukrainian forces in the Donetsk region have struggled to seize back significant territory. <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111348"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001111348"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/alistair-macdonald" itemprop="url" rel="author">Alistair MacDonald</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name">Oksana Pyrozhok</span> | Photographs by Serhii Korovayny for The Wall Street Journal</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 5, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> CHASIV YAR, Ukraine—Some of Ukraine&#39;s biggest gains in its counteroffensive have come around the city of Bakhmut, which Russia seized in May after <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/36-hours-in-bakhmut-one-units-desperate-battle-to-hold-back-the-russians-72e30f01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">months of bloody fighting</a> . But soldiers near there say advances have slowed in recent days amid stiff Russian defense and counterattacks, denting hopes that Kyiv could soon <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-aims-for-comeback-in-shattered-bakhmut-after-wagner-revolt-45707720?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">retake the city</a> .</p><p> Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky visited the Bakhmut front in late July to hail gains to the north and south of the city, taking the heights and overlooking the Russian troops hemmed within the ruins below.</p><p> Fighting is now focusing around the town of Klishchiivka, some 5 miles to the south, and in the direction of the M03 highway to the north. Ukrainian soldiers say recent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-war-counteroffensive-frontlines-russia-add3e4e4?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">gains have been small</a> , in the face of heavy artillery bombardments, improved Russian performance on the battlefield and their own limited manpower and equipment.</p><p> Ukraine&#39;s counteroffensive, now in its third month, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">has been slow going</a> , bogged down by strong Russian defensive positions, mines and helicopter assaults, particularly in the south. That raises difficult questions about the scale of <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the task facing the Ukrainian forces</a> . </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830073?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky visited forces in Donetsk in late July.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Ukrainian Presidential Press Office/Zuma Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Progress around Bakhmut in the east had been faster as Russia had less time to prepare defensive positions after the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/video/series/shadow-men/shadow-men-inside-wagner-russias-secret-war-company/29735C37-0B4E-4E70-8E8C-C46FB711370C?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Wagner paramilitary group</a> finally took the city. Bakhmut had become <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/36-hours-in-bakhmut-one-units-desperate-battle-to-hold-back-the-russians-72e30f01?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a symbol of Ukrainian resistance</a> during months of brutal fighting, and Russia is expected to pour resources into its dogged defense, given the city was one of the few gains it made in recent months—and at the cost of tens of thousands of lives.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “It&#39;s a tough fight, and we need more people and more equipment,” said a combat medic, who came for coffee to a gas station where front-line soldiers stock up on fuel and food.</p><p> “We are exhausted,” he said.</p><p> A Ukrainian official said Monday that Ukraine had liberated 0.7 square mile in the Bakhmut area, in the previous week. Russia still controls around 20% of Ukraine.</p><p> Officials from Russia and its proxies have said on social media that their forces have repelled several Ukrainian attacks. Yan Gagin, an official at the so-called Donetsk People&#39;s Republic, a Russian proxy state that claims Ukraine&#39;s Donetsk region as its territory, said that the fighting around Bakhmut remains the hottest part of the front line. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830024?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Russian forces struck the Palace of Culture in Chasiv Yar, a town around 3 miles from the city of Bakhmut, at the end of June. The building had been used as a place for providing medical aid. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829999?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Ukrainian soldiers emerge from a basement post in Chasiv Yar.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “It&#39;s slow, it&#39;s just really slow,” said Dougie Young,</p> a Scottish medical volunteer who has been working around Bakhmut.<p></p><p> The British army veteran said that at the end of last year and the start of 2023 the fighting often involved soldiers trading small-arms fire, but has now reduced to mainly artillery bombardment. The injuries he treats are mainly related to those inflicted by fragmentation and shrapnel.</p><p> Young and several Ukrainian soldiers in the area said that infantry attacks and medical evacuations are made harder because artillery bombardments have stripped the area of cover, by destroying buildings and trees.</p><p> By evening Thursday, Russia had fired 580 times on Ukrainian positions in the Bakhmut area, a bombardment which they had been keeping up for days, said Serhiy Cherevaty, the spokesman of the Eastern Group of the Armed Forces of Ukraine. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=8ADA4C1F-0418-43CF-B08A-6EBE0A657F3A&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The recent turmoil in Russia could provide an opportunity for Ukraine&#39;s battlefield forces. WSJ reporter Ian Lovett and retired Brigadier Gen. Mark Kimmitt break down what might be next for the Ukrainian counteroffensive. Photo Illustration: Jeremy Shuback/WSJ<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>Ukraine has been targeting Russian positions with its own munitions, employing Western <strong>&nbsp;</strong> and old Soviet systems.</p><p> At an artillery position around 4½ miles from the front line, members of a unit that operates a German howitzer—a PzH2000, or Panzerhaubitze—said they spend much of the day driving to different positions, hitting Russian artillery and infantry units.</p><p> “We pushed the Russians back around 1 kilometer, but now they are coming back,” said Andriy, the commander of the howitzer. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829987?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Ukrainian soldier who goes by the call sign Doom said Russian forces were becoming better trained. </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830004?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Movement by Ukraine&#39;s military in Chasiv Yar has become more complicated as Russian surveillance improves.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Just over a week ago their encampment, hidden in the forest, was spotted by a Russian drone. Russian artillery then rained some 50 shells down on the position for around an hour as the crew hid in a bunker, the commander said.</p><p> When they emerged the trees had been flattened but the howitzer only had shrapnel marks.</p><p> Local soldiers say that the Russians are using many more drones now and appear to have more than the Ukrainian forces in the area. At Chasiv Yar, a front-line town some 3½ miles from Bakhmut, soldiers scanned the skies looking for drones and walked under the lines of trees that bracket the streets here. Frequent bursts of artillery fire sounded through the mainly deserted streets of a town where few buildings appear to have escaped damage from the bombardment.</p><p> Aside from drones, Russians appear to be developing in other ways, including through encrypting more of their communications to stop Ukraine eavesdropping, according to an intelligence official.</p><p> Many soldiers agreed.</p><p> “The Russians are more trained and more creative,” said a soldier at Chasiv Yar whose call sign is Doom. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829992?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Shelling left buildings in Chasiv Yar in rubble.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Still, the intelligence official and most Ukrainian soldiers say that the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-fends-off-drone-attack-as-moscow-warns-west-over-jet-fighters-f6db1bb0?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">Wagner forces that took Bakhmut earlier in the year</a> were better than the regular Russian soldiers that replaced them. Wagner officers are more experienced and the militia, which at times used waves of recruits from prisons to attack in often suicidal missions, were more persistent. If beaten back, Wagner would keep attacking a position from several angles, in a way that regular troops wouldn&#39;t always do, they said.</p><p> Soldiers say jet fighters are needed if Ukraine is to make progress here without a large loss of life.</p><p> Despite the increased reliance on artillery, infantry assaults do still happen. On Thursday, Russian soldiers attacked a position south of Bakhmut and took some 200 yards of land before later abandoning it following Ukrainian counterattacks, according to a soldier from a motorized infantry division.</p><p> The soldier, who uses the call sign Hightower after a particularly tall character in the American movie “Police Academy,” said that Russian soldiers were killed but that up to 40 Ukrainian soldiers were injured.</p><p> Like many of the Ukrainian soldiers now fighting around Bakhmut, Hightower is a veteran of the area. He was there when it fell in May and his ambition is to be there when Ukraine retakes it. But while he is confident this will happen, he is steeling himself for what is to come.</p><p> “The Russians put a lot of effort into getting this city, that is why for them it is an important city, too,” he said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830027?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Chasiv Yar is occupied chiefly by Ukraine&#39;s military forces, with few civilians remaining.</p></figcaption></figure></div><p class="articleTagLine"> —Anastasiia Malenko contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Alistair MacDonald at <a href="mailto:Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Alistair.Macdonald@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-struggles-to-retake-bakhmut-from-dogged-russian-fighters-c8945b93<author><![CDATA[Alistair MacDonald]]></author><category>乌克兰</category><category>航空航天/国防</category><category>国防设备/产品</category><category>工业品</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>武装部队</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>乌克兰</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>armed forces</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>航天</category><category>防御</category><category>国防装备</category><category>产品</category><category>工业品</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Tank Tops, Toilet Trips and Lies: What Headhunters Can See]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Recruiters share their wildest stories from working with applicants seeking jobs and the companies considering hiring them <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828473/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Robert Neubecker <span>Robert Neubecker</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105123"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001105123"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/francesca-fontana" itemprop="url" rel="author">Francesca Fontana</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Updated Aug. 5, 2023 12:01 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tank-tops-toilet-trips-and-lies-what-headhunters-can-see-b89a4f14"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> <em>We spoke with executive recruiters about hiring today. Interviews have been edited and condensed for length and clarity.</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Faking a car accident</h3><p> We had placed a candidate in a temporary position, a light industrial role in Houston. It was his first week, and that day he was late for work. He said it was because he got in a car accident, and he ended up just not showing up at all.</p><p> We didn&#39;t ask for one, but he sent us a picture of his car as proof that he was really in an accident. One of our recruiters noticed that the photo didn&#39;t look like it was in the right season. I think in the picture the leaves on the trees in the background had turned, but it was summer out.</p><p> We ended up just searching “car accident” in Google Images and that picture was one of the first results that came up. It was, like, stock photography. We then informed him that it would be his last day.</p><p> He could have overslept or something, and people are pretty understanding that mistakes happen and no one&#39;s perfect. The best thing you can do is just be honest about it, not make something up. The whole thing was so silly, because no one even asked him to send anything.</p><p> <em>—Keith Wolf, Murray Resources</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Dressing for success</h3><p> Early in my career, I was recruiting for a mid-level remote developer position for a tech company. I always prepare my candidates for their interviews, so I hopped on the phone with him and went over the basics: The interview would be over Zoom, but make sure you&#39;re still professional from the waist up, don&#39;t wear a hat, that kind of thing. He seemed ready to go, and I had confidence—he had a great background.</p><p> The interview only ended up being like 15 minutes long, which is not a good sign, and the client sent us a feedback email pretty quickly, giving us a heads up that this candidate had been calling from inside his garage, wearing a white tank top and a backwards hat and smoking a cigar. We were like, this cannot be real.</p><p> My account manager assured me that this wasn&#39;t my fault, and he called the candidate to give him the feedback and ask what his reasoning was behind all of it. The candidate said he just needed to take a load off, due to his nerves and stuff. He really thought that what he was doing wasn&#39;t a big deal, which is pretty wild.</p><p> The candidate had decent longevity at other companies, so we were really confused. But we didn&#39;t work with him after that, unfortunately.</p><p> <em>—Molly Hansen, Hirewell</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><h3> Bathroom calls</h3><p> The thing I am most surprised by is when candidates are comfortable going to the bathroom while on a call with you. We can hear everything. My colleague once asked me, “Are you sure that wasn&#39;t just a sink running?” and I was like, “No, I think running a sink usually isn&#39;t followed by a flush.” I&#39;ve had it happen more times than I can count on two hands.</p><p> One time, I also had an initial phone screen scheduled with a candidate about a software engineer job and they picked up the call while in the shower. I could hear water running, and they said, “Oh, I&#39;m actually in the shower right now.” I asked, “Are you just getting into the shower?” And they said, “No, no I&#39;m in the shower.” I was just like, you could have just let this go to voicemail! It was pretty mind-blowing. And I told them that we should reschedule.</p><p> Funnily enough, the person ended up being a great candidate and I placed them in a role.</p><p> <em>—Matthew Mulcahy, Hirewell</em> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          smallrule
"><div class="wsj-article-page-rule"></div></div><p> Write to Francesca Fontana at <a href="mailto:francesca.fontana@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">francesca.fontana@wsj.com</a> .</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Sat, 05 Aug 2023 04:01:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tank-tops-toilet-trips-and-lies-what-headhunters-can-see-b89a4f14</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/tank-tops-toilet-trips-and-lies-what-headhunters-can-see-b89a4f14<author><![CDATA[Francesca Fontana]]></author><category>管理</category><category>管理层变动</category><category>劳工/人事</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>招聘</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>管理</category><category>管理举措</category><category>劳动</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>招聘</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[America’s Most Tech-Forward City Has Doubts About Self-Driving Cars]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Alphabet 旗下的 Waymo 和通用汽车旗下的 Cruise 正在努力争取旧金山居民和官员的支持，这是它们在全国范围内扩张的主要障碍。 <figure><img src="https://m.wsj.net/video-atmo/20230803/b1d0b61c-45ca-49c8-89e6-284b916a2edb/1/sequence01_1000x562.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> 2023 年 7 月 25 日星期二，一辆 Cruise 自动驾驶汽车停在加利福尼亚州旧金山 Mission 区建筑区的十字路口中间。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001109813"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001109813"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/meghan-bobrowsky" itemprop="url" rel="author">Meghan Bobrowsky</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/miles-kruppa" itemprop="url" rel="author">​​Miles Kruppa</a></span> Poppy Lynch 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 4 日晚上 9:00 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/americas-most-tech-forward-city-has-doubts-about-self-driving-cars-d6b098e0"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>旧金山——这座城市的居民比世界其他地方的人更早地接受了电脑、互联网和手机。他们对自动驾驶汽车不太确定。</p><p>突然之间，橙色和白色的无人驾驶 Cruise 和 Waymo 汽车似乎无处不在。一些急救人员表示，它们妨碍了交通，行人也在社交媒体上发布了有关汽车滑稽行为的报道。他们与至少两只宠物相撞。一个反汽车活动组织在汽车引擎盖上放置了橙色交通锥，将其冻结在原地，同时制作了病毒式特技视频。</p><p> San Francisco&#39;s reaction is a preview of the challenges Cruise, majority owned by General Motors, and Waymo, part of Google parent <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/GOOG" class="">Alphabet</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> will face as they expand to cities across the US Both companies have invested billions in driverless cars, hoping they will become massive businesses, and they still need to win hearts and minds.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p>旧金山是一座拥有约 80 万人口的城市，已经进行了数千英里的自动驾驶汽车测试，并且一些居民是常客。现在，这些公司希望提供可以与<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/LYFT" class="company-name">Lyft</a>和<a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/UBER" class="">Uber</a>竞争的叫车业务<span class="company-name-type">。</span></p><p>如果这些公司如愿以偿，旧金山将成为首批使用自动驾驶汽车进行交通运输的大型城市实验之一的归零地。这座如今以科技人口而闻名的城市，也一直是政治抗议、花童和城市性格的激烈守护者的中心。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="875" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829285?width=700&amp;height=875" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">旧金山卡斯特罗区第 18 街的一辆 Cruise 自动驾驶汽车。该公司在该市拥有数百辆汽车，正在寻求州政府的许可以扩大其业务，并向乘客收取全天所有行程费用。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> The California Public Utilities Commission, which regulates passenger transportation, is scheduled to vote this month on whether to allow GM&#39;s Cruise to expand its presence in San Francisco and to allow it and Alphabet&#39;s Waymo to charge for rides at all times.投票已被推迟两次，该机构将于下周举行听证会，听取各公司对安全问题清单的回应。</p><p>旧金山交通局交通主管杰弗里·图姆林 (Jeffrey Tumlin) 表示：“我们认为自动驾驶汽车太棒了，我们相信有一天它们会比人类司机更安全。” “到目前为止，业界尚未证明这一点。”</p><p> Cruise 和 Waymo 正在反击。两家公司的高管已开始更加紧迫地向公众和政府官员展示他们的主张，并提供了他们所说的显示其车辆安全优势的数据。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="1228" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/f83ce730-5d94-4570-be1e-a5253dee54fd-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> Cruise首席执行官凯尔·沃格特(Kyle Vogt)在接受采访时表示，如果官员们放慢自动驾驶汽车的推出速度，就会导致更多人受到伤害，并援引公司数据显示，自动驾驶汽车的出现与碰撞事故的减少有关。沃格特说，自今年年初以来，Cruise 在旧金山道路上的汽车数量已增加了五倍。该公司在全国拥有近 400 辆汽车，其中大部分都位于该技术中心。</p><p>沃格特说：“任何新事物，尤其是一种看似神奇的技术，都会引起很多问题并引起很多关注。” “关注会引起争议。”</p><p> Waymo 上个月要求乘客写信给州官员。据称，如果旧金山州投“反对”票，该公司可能无法继续在旧金山运营。</p><p>克鲁斯在几家报纸上刊登了整版广告，称“人类是糟糕的司机”，并列举了去年美国因车祸造成近 43,000 人死亡的情况。</p><p>目前，Cruise 在旧金山提供夜间付费乘车服务。 Waymo 尚未获得该州提供付费乘车服务的许可，但人们可以免费乘坐其汽车。两者都有等待加入应用程序的名单。</p><p>交通锥背后的组织 Safe Street Rebel 在州委员会投票之前协调了这一噱头，作为对 Cruise 和 Waymo 扩张的为期一周的抗议。成员们戴着手套和面罩在街道上徘徊，在经常被发现的地方寻找汽车，比如狭长地带公园周围的街道。这些锥体混淆了汽车的传感器，其中一些传感器放置在车顶上，将它们停在原地。</p><p>在州委员会撤回投票后，活动人士声称推迟投票应归咎于部分原因，并赞扬州官员对扩张计划进行更多审查。</p><p> Cruise 和 Waymo 已经花费了数十亿美元来尝试建立按需出租车服务，他们希望这种服务最终能够在不需要人类司机的情况下产生更大的利润。到目前为止，他们的业务产生的收入微乎其微。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="800" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830127?width=600" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>通用汽车报告称，去年 Cruise 的销售额为 1.02 亿美元，成本和费用为 33 亿美元。首席执行官</p>玛丽·巴拉 (Mary Barra) 6 月份表示，该公司正处于向自动驾驶汽车转型的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/regulators-launch-probe-of-gms-cruise-autonomous-driving-system-11671201585?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">早期阶段</a>，高管们表示，该公司的目标是到本十年末年收入达到 500 亿美元。<p></p><p>自 2020 年以来，Waymo 已从 Alphabet 和外部投资者那里筹集了超过 57 亿美元的资金<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/activist-investor-calls-on-google-parent-alphabet-to-slash-costs-11668528859?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">。Alphabet 面临股东压力，要求减少对 Waymo 和其他投机性企业的支出</a>，因此没有单独报告其财务业绩。</p><p><a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="">亚马逊</a><span class="company-name-type">旗下的</span>Zoox 也在旧金山街道上测试了其自动驾驶技术，并正在开发一款专为出租车服务设计的定制四四方方车辆。该公司拒绝透露何时开始在该市部署这些汽车。</p><p> Cruise 和 Waymo 高管谴责了 Safe Street Rebel 活动人士，他们在汽车上安装了锥体并将视频上传到 TikTok。 Waymo 表示这是一种破坏行为。该组织后来删除了这些视频。</p><p> “这是一辆移动的多吨车辆。它不是玩具，”Waymo 联合首席执行官 Tekedra Mawakana 在接受采访时表示。她补充说，该公司计划在其汽车遭到破坏时向当局寻求帮助。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/a1911cdd-8ae0-4cf4-9d8a-13f84ae30f1c.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>沃格特表示，他认为现在不是“玩愚蠢游戏”的时候。</p><p>安全街叛乱组织表示，该组织的抗议活动并未破坏财产。活动人士认为，这些汽车对步行、骑自行车和公共交通等其他城市出行方式构成了威胁。</p><p>除了旧金山之外，菲尼克斯还有数百辆自动驾驶汽车，更多的自动驾驶汽车正在洛杉矶、迈阿密、达拉斯、德克萨斯州奥斯汀和田纳西州纳什维尔部署进行测试。三年前，只有少数几个城市有测试车辆城市。</p><p> Cruise 今年 3 月向加州机动车辆管理局申请了在全州范围内扩张的许可，并以高达每小时 55 英里的速度运营其汽车。</p><p>据加州机动车辆部门提交的文件显示，此后，Cruise 已向至少 14 个加州城市和县的官员发送了电子邮件，其中包括偏远的圣华金河谷（San Joaquin Valley）拥有 12,200 人的纽曼县（Newman），告知他们该公司在那里扩张的计划。部门。其中一封电子邮件显示，该公司表示将首先在每个新市场推出五辆汽车。</p><p> Cruise 发言人表示，作为全州申请的一部分，该公司通知了官员，最终希望在加州各地运营，但计划首先在主要城市推出其车辆。</p><p> Waymo 于 2 月份开始在洛杉矶提供无人驾驶乘车服务，本周又宣布计划在奥斯汀提供乘车服务。</p><p>今年五月，旧金山<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/california-regulator-looking-into-anonymous-letter-alleging-cruises-robotaxi-service-wasnt-ready-for-launch-11657811102?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">市官员</a>致函该州，表达了对该市扩建计划的担忧。他们列出了一些事件，其中一辆 Waymo 驶入建筑工地，差点滚入露天沟渠，消防员需要打破 Cruise 的车窗以阻止其驶入火灾现场。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=504B3EFA-E989-4106-87DD-42B4D461DD23&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Famericas-most-tech-forward-city-has-doubts-about-self-driving-cars-d6b098e0&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">一辆 Waymo 自动驾驶汽车在旧金山 Mission 区一条繁忙的街道上转弯，险些撞上另一辆车。市政府官员正在寻求更多数据来帮助他们确定无人驾驶汽车的安全影响。<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-829286?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">当一辆 Cruise 汽车沿着旧金山杜博斯三角区的卡斯特罗街行驶时，旁观者正在观看这一场景。一家无人驾驶汽车公司表示，该市只有一半居民愿意乘坐无人驾驶的汽车。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>市政府官员表示，近几个月来，涉及 Cruise 和 Waymo 车辆的事故报告数量增加了两倍。交通总监图姆林表示，官员们需要自动驾驶汽车公司提供更多公开数据来得出有关其安全性的结论，该市正在朝着这一目标取得进展。</p><p> Cruise 和 Waymo 均表示，他们的汽车没有造成任何交通死亡事故。 Waymo 表示，在全自动驾驶模式下，其自动驾驶汽车在首次行驶 100 万英里时并未与人类驾驶员发生任何碰撞。</p><p> Cruise 的一位发言人表示，只需乘坐一次就能让怀疑论者转变为信徒。他援引内部数据表示，约90%的乘坐过顺风车的人愿意再乘坐一次。</p><p>曾领导谷歌自动驾驶汽车项目（现称为 Waymo）的塞巴斯蒂安·特龙 (Sebastian Thrun) 表示，如果允许汽车更广泛地运营，人们将开始看到好处。他说，当他运行这个项目时，人们只需要在车里七到八分钟就可以放松并更加适应这项技术。</p><p> 6 月傍晚，退休副城市检察官珍妮·理查森 (Janie Richardson) 带着两只狗在旧金山太平洋高地附近过马路，当时她说一辆自动驾驶 Cruise 车辆驶入十字路口，撞上了她的一个黑色拉布拉多犬。 ，黛利拉。</p><p>她说，大约 10 分钟后，克鲁斯的一名技术人员到达了现场，并递给她一张纸，标题为“为参与克鲁斯事件的其他人提供的讲义”。据《华尔街日报》看到的信件副本显示，除其他细节外，其中还列出了该车的保险信息。</p><p>黛利拉没有受伤，但理查森说她以前没有过多考虑自动驾驶汽车，现在希望它们离开旧金山。克鲁斯发言人拒绝就具体案件发表评论。</p><p>沃格特批评该市宣传他所谓的误导性数据。他说，克鲁斯在过去一年中与市政府官员进行了 50 多次交谈，听取他们的担忧，并根据反馈对服务进行了更改。</p><p> Waymo 联合首席执行官 Mawakana 反驳了居民反对这些车辆的说法，并列举了 10 万多人已在等候名单上登记使用 Waymo 出租车服务的情况。</p><p> “每天都有人给我打电话、发电子邮件并抱怨他们等了多久才获得这项服务，”马瓦卡纳说。</p><p>从事教育工作的玛雅·沃尔德曼 (Maya Waldman) 早期在旧金山报名成为 Waymo 的无薪测试骑手，并已驾驶该车行驶了 5,000 多英里。</p><p>沃尔德曼表示，在参与该计划之前，她对自动驾驶汽车了解不多，但现在感觉自动驾驶汽车比传统的叫车服务更安全。除此之外，她不会受到随机分类的人类司机的摆布。</p><p> “每次我叫 Waymo 时，都是同一个司机，”她说。 “当我乘坐 Lyft 或 Uber 时（有时我仍然会使用它们），我永远不知道会得到什么。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
